Week 2 Assignment – Tesla Deliveries Analysis and Machine Learning Pipeline

Overview

This project focuses on analyzing Tesla deliveries and production data from 2015 to 2025 using data analysis and machine learning techniques. The objective is to understand delivery trends, perform feature engineering, build predictive models, and evaluate their performance using standard machine learning metrics. The project follows a complete machine learning workflow from data exploration and preprocessing to forecasting and statistical testing.

Dataset

Dataset Used: Tesla EV Deliveries and Production Data (2015–2025)

The dataset contains information related to Tesla vehicle deliveries, production units, pricing, battery specifications, vehicle range, charging infrastructure, and regional performance across different years and models.

Objectives

• Analyze Tesla deliveries and production data using machine learning techniques.

• Explore and understand the dataset through data analysis and visualization.

• Perform data preprocessing and feature engineering.

• Create lag and rolling mean features to capture historical patterns.

• Build and evaluate a Linear Regression model.

• Perform 5 Fold Cross Validation to assess model stability.

• Optimize a Random Forest model using GridSearchCV.

• Analyze feature importance and identify key predictors.

• Perform stationarity testing using the Augmented Dickey Fuller Test.

• Generate forecasts and compare predicted values with actual observations.

Technologies Used

• Python

• Pandas

• NumPy

• Matplotlib

• Seaborn

• Scikit Learn

• Statsmodels

• Google Colab

Project Workflow

1. Data Loading and Understanding

The dataset was loaded into a Pandas DataFrame and explored using shape, columns, info(), and describe() to understand its structure and available features.

2. Data Quality Checks

The dataset was checked for missing values and duplicate records to ensure data quality before analysis.

3. Exploratory Data Analysis

Several visualizations were created to understand trends and relationships within the data including deliveries by model, deliveries by region, correlation heatmap, production versus deliveries scatter plot, and time trend analysis.

4. Data Preprocessing

Categorical features such as Region, Model, and Source_Type were converted into numerical form using Label Encoding.

5. Feature Engineering

Two additional features were created: Deliveries_Lag1 and Rolling_Mean_3. These features help capture historical delivery trends and improve predictive performance.

6. Model Development

A Linear Regression model was trained to predict Estimated Deliveries and evaluated using Mean Absolute Error (MAE), Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE), and R² Score.

Five Fold Cross Validation was performed to evaluate model stability and consistency.

A Random Forest model was optimized using GridSearchCV to identify the best hyperparameter combination and improve prediction accuracy.

7. Feature Importance Analysis

Feature importance scores from the Random Forest model were analyzed to identify the most influential variables affecting delivery predictions.

8. Time Series Analysis

The Augmented Dickey Fuller (ADF) Test was performed on Estimated Deliveries to determine whether the series is stationary.

9. Forecasting

A forecast table was created to compare Actual Values, Predicted Values, and Error Percentage for the first twenty test observations.

Key Learnings

• Data preprocessing and feature engineering techniques.

• Exploratory Data Analysis using visualizations.

• Regression model development and evaluation.

• Cross Validation and Hyperparameter Tuning.

• Feature Importance Analysis.

• Time Series Stationarity Testing.

• Forecasting and prediction evaluation.

Conclusion

This project demonstrates a complete machine learning workflow using Tesla deliveries and production data. Through data exploration, preprocessing, feature engineering, model training, validation, and forecasting, meaningful insights were obtained regarding Tesla delivery patterns and production trends. The project highlights how machine learning techniques can be applied to analyze historical business data and generate reliable predictions.

